humanit\u00e9 en p\u00e9ril (Disquette Imagine pour C64/128)|magazine=[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]|issue=46|publisher=Jean-Pierre Roger|date=October 1987|page=53|lang=fr}}</ref><br />15/20<ref name=\"TiltC64sf2\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Tilt/tilt_numero049/TILT%20-%20n%b049%20-%20decembre%201987%20-%20page092%20et%20page093.jpg|title=Dossier: 41 <<spaces invaders>> au Tiltoscope - Slap Fight|magazine=[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]|issue=49|publisher=Jean-Pierre Roger|date=December 1987|pages=92-93|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| 13/20<ref name=\"TiltThomsonSTsf\">{{cite magazine|last=Huyghues-Lacour|first=Alain|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Tilt/tilt_numero055/TILT%20-%20n%b0%2055%20-%20juin%201988%20-%20page052%20et%20page053.jpg|title=Tubes: Slapfight - Les envahisseurs (Disquette Imagine pour Atari ST) / Version Thomson|magazine=[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]|issue=55|publisher=Jean-Pierre Roger|date=June 1988|pages=52-53|lang=fr}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| 14/20<ref name=\"TiltThomsonSTsf\"/>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Your Sinclair]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 9/10<ref name=\"YSZXSsf1\">{{cite magazine|last=Gerrard|first=Mike|url=https://archive.org/stream/your-sinclair-21#page/n65/mode/1up|title=Screen Shots - Part 2: Slap Fight|magazine=[[Your Sinclair]]|issue=21|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=September 1987|page=66}}</ref><br />82\u00b0/100\u00b0<ref name=\"YSZXSsf2\">{{cite magazine|last=Berkmann|first=Markus|url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/infoseek/magazines/your-sinclair/56#76|title=Bargain Basement - Slapfight|magazine=[[Your Sinclair]]|issue=56|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=August 1990|page=76|access-date=24 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017013155/http://live.worldofspectrum.org/infoseek/magazines/your-sinclair/56#76|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| 80%<ref name=\"Z!64C64sf1\">{{cite magazine|last1=Sumner|first1=Paul|last2=Brennan|first2=Ciar\u00e1n|last3=Jarratt|first3=Steve|authorlink3=Steve Jarratt|url=https://archive.org/stream/zzapp_64_issue_028_600dpi/Zzap640028Hi#page/n89/mode/2up|title=Zzap! Test - Slap Fight|magazine=[[Zzap!64]]|issue=28|publisher=[[Newsfield Publications]]|date=August 1987|pages=90-91}}</ref><br />60%<ref name=\"Z!64C64sf2\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/zzap64-magazine-062#page/n47/mode/1up|title=Zzap! Budget: Cor Blimey! The Budget Bit! - Slapfight|magazine=[[Zzap!64]]|issue=62|publisher=[[Newsfield Publications]]|date=June 1990|page=46}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n|}\n\nAccording to Tatsuya Uemura, not many arcade boards were produced for ''Slap Fight'' in Japan but proved to be popular among players.<ref name=\"G49\"/> Japanese magazine ''Game Machine'' listed it on their 1 September 1986 issue as being the seventh most-successful table arcade unit of the year, outperforming titles such as ''[[Ikari Warriors]]'' and ''[[Gradius (video game)|Gradius]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - \u30c6\u30fc\u30d6\u30eb\u578bTV\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u6a5f (Table Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30de\u30b7\u30f3|Game Machine]]|issue=291|publisher=[[:ja:\u30a2\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30ba\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u901a\u4fe1\u793e|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=1 September 1986|page=23|lang=ja}}</ref> [[Den of Geek]] noted its weapon system and multiple ways to kill enemies.<ref name=\"T-Hdog\">{{cite web|last=Lambie|first=Ryan|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/games/58480/toaplan-the-rise-and-fall-of-japans-greatest-shooting-game-company|title=Toaplan: the rise and fall of Japan's greatest shooting game company|work=[[Den of Geek]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=21 June 2018|access-date=2020-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621073806/http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/games/58480/toaplan-the-rise-and-fall-of-japans-greatest-shooting-game-company|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nAccording to Masahiro Yuge, some of the ideas implemented in ''Slap Fight'' would later go on to influence development of ''Truxton''.<ref name=\"TSCb\"/> A spiritual successor, ''Grind Stormer'' (1993), uses a weapon power-up system reminiscent of ''Slap Fight''.<ref>{{cite web|author=blackoak|url=http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-vv/|title=1993 V-V Toaplan Interview|website=shmuplations.com|access-date=2020-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107034510/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-vv/|archive-date=2019-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zverloff|first=Nick|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/v-five-grind-stormer/|title=V-Five / Grind Stormer|publisher=Hardcore Gaming 101|date=29 June 2011|access-date=2020-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403000300/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/v-five-grind-stormer/|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Joscelyne|first=Svend|url=https://spong.com/feature/10110562/Interview-All-Your-Base-Cave-CCO-Tsuneki-Ikeda|title=Interviews// All Your Base: Cave CCO Tsuneki Ikeda|work=SPOnG|publisher=SPOnG.com Limited|date=8 December 2011|access-date=2020-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003230713/http://spong.com/feature/10110562/Interview-All-Your-Base-Cave-CCO-Tsuneki-Ikeda|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In more recent years, the rights to the game and many other IPs from Toaplan are now owned by Tatsujin, a company named after ''Truxton''{{'}}s Japanese title that was founded in 2017 by Yuge, who are affiliated with arcade manufacturer exA-Arcadia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tatsujin.tokyo/custom.html|title=\u30e9\u30a4\u30bb\u30f3\u30b9\u4e8b\u696d|publisher=TATSUJIN Co., Ltd.|date=2019|access-date=2020-04-24|lang=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225203847/http://tatsujin.tokyo/custom.html|archive-date=2018-12-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bravo|first=Roberto|url=https://www.gamercafe.cl/2018/09/12/nueva-compania-tatsujin-asegura-tener-gran-parte-de-las-ips-de-la-extinta-toaplan/|title=Nueva compa\u00f1\u00eda \u00abTatsujin\u00bb asegura tener gran parte de las IPs de la extinta Toaplan|publisher=Gamercafe|date=12 September 2018|access-date=2020-04-24|lang=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021030437/https://www.gamercafe.cl/2018/09/12/nueva-compania-tatsujin-asegura-tener-gran-parte-de-las-ips-de-la-extinta-toaplan/|archive-date=2019-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://exa.ac/en/editors/tatsujin/|title=Tatsujin|publisher=exA-Arcadia|date=2019|access-date=2020-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021030706/https://exa.ac/en/editors/tatsujin/?v=a99877f71bd9|archive-date=2019-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bravo|first=Roberto|url=https://www.gamercafe.cl/2019/01/25/tatsujin-los-duenos-de-toaplan-anuncian-que-estan-trabajando-para-exa-arcadia/|title=Tatsujin, los due\u00f1os de Toaplan, anuncian que est\u00e1n trabajando para exA-Arcadia|publisher=Gamercafe|date=25 January 2019|access-date=2020-04-24|lang=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031057/https://www.gamercafe.cl/2019/01/25/tatsujin-los-duenos-de-toaplan-anuncian-que-estan-trabajando-para-exa-arcadia/|archive-date=2019-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/408/G040821/20190125146/|title=\uff3bJAEPO2019\uff3dTATSUJIN\u3084\u30ca\u30c4\u30e1\u30a2\u30bf\u30ea\u306e\u53c2\u5165\u304c\u767a\u8868\u3055\u308c\u305fexA-Arcadia\u3002\u51fa\u5c55\u30b3\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u306e\u6a21\u69d8\u3092\u7d39\u4ecb|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=26 January 2019|access-date=2020-04-24|lang=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031252/https://www.4gamer.net/games/408/G040821/20190125146/|archive-date=2019-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/arcade/584094-alcon ''Alcon''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/alcon/3030-11840/ ''Alcon''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=6843 ''Alcon''] at [[Killer List of Videogames]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/alcon ''Alcon''] at [[MobyGames]]\n* [http://privat.bahnhof.se/wb831590/toaplansite/allyourbase/slapfight/index.html ''Slap Fight''] at The Toaplan Museum\n\n{{Toaplan video games}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Japan|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slap Fight}}\n[[Category:1986 video games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Atari ST games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis-only games]]\n[[Category:Shoot 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Tengen (company) games]]\n[[Category:Toaplan games]]\n[[Category:Vertically scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Martin Galway]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Masahiro Yuge]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Yuzo Koshiro]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2050s]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the scrolling shooter arcade game|the form of striking a person|Slapping (disambiguation){{!}}Slap}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Slap Fight\n|image         = Slap Fight arcade flyer.jpg\n|developer     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Toaplan]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Probe Software]]<br><small>(CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>[[Imagine Software]] <small>(C64)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>Abersoft Limited <small>(ST)</small><br>M.N.M Software<br><small>(Mega Drive)</small>}}\n|publisher     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Taito]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|Imagine Software<br><small>(C64/CPC/ST/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>France Image Logiciel<br><small>(Thomson MO5/TO8)</small><br>[[Ocean Software|The Hit Squad]]<br><small>(C64/CPC/ZX Spectrum)</small><br>'''Mega Drive'''{{vgrelease|JP|[[Tengen (company)|Tengen]]|KOR|[[Samsung]]}}}}\n|composer      = Masahiro Yuge\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Sega Mega Drive]], [[Thomson MO5]], [[Thomson TO8]], [[ZX Spectrum]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1986 in video gaming|1986]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 1986<ref name=\"ATVGL:JaO1971-2005\">{{cite book|last=Akagi|first=Masumi|url=https://archive.org/stream/ArcadeGameList1971-2005#page/n44/mode/1up|title=\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30fc (Taito); \u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3 (Toa Plan); Taito America|work=\u30a2\u30fc\u30b1\u30fc\u30c9TV\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8 \u56fd\u5185\u2022\u6d77\u5916\u7de8 (1971-2005)|edition=1st|publisher=[[:ja:\u30a2\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30ba\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u901a\u4fe1\u793e|Amusement News Agency]]|date=13 October 2006|pages=43, 50, 156|isbn=978-4990251215|language=ja}}</ref>|NA|September 1986<ref name=\"ATVGL:JaO1971-2005\"/>|EU|1986}} '''Amstrad CPC'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[1987 in video gaming|1987]]}} '''Commodore 64'''{{vgrelease|EU|1987|NA|July [[1989 in video gaming|1989]]}} '''Thomson MO5'''{{vgrelease|FRA|1987}} '''Thomson TO8'''{{vgrelease|FRA|1987}} '''ZX Spectrum'''{{vgrelease|EU|1987}} '''Atari ST'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[1988 in video gaming|1988]]|NA|March 1989}} '''Mega Drive'''{{vgrelease|JP|11 June [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]|KOR|1993}}}}\n|genre         = [[Shoot 'em up#Types|Vertically scrolling shooter]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]], [[Arcade cabinet#Cocktail or table cabinets|cocktail]]\n|arcade system = Toaplan Slap Fight<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=643&page=1#1567|title=Toaplan Slapfight Hardware (Other)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-11-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916045029/http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=643&page=1#1567|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|cpu           = (2x) [[Zilog Z80|Z80]] (@ 6 [[MHz]]),<br>[[Motorola 68705|M68705]] (@ 1 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\"/><ref name=\"ah1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=slap-fight&page=detail&id=2470|title=Slap Fight|website=arcade-history.com|access-date=2019-11-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008013139/https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=slap-fight&page=detail&id=2470|archive-date=8 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|sound         = (2x) [[General Instrument AY-3-8910|GI AY-3-8910]] (@ 1.5 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\"/><ref name=\"ah1\"/>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 240 x 280 pixels (Vertical), 256 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Slap Fight'''''|\u30b9\u30e9\u30c3\u30d7\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8|''Surappu Faito''|also known as '''''Alcon''''' in North America|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 1986 [[Shoot 'em up#Types|vertically scrolling shooter]] [[Arcade game|arcade]] [[video game]] originally developed by [[Toaplan]] and published by [[Taito]]. Set on the colonized fictional planet of Theron in the future, where an alien race led by Gaudy have invaded the human-controlled location, players assume the role of an Allied League of Cosmic Nations (ALCON) fighter pilot taking control of the SW475 [[List of fictional spacecraft#Space fighters|space fighter]] craft in a effort to counterattack the invaders. Initially launched for the arcades, the game was later [[Porting#Porting in gaming|ported]] to other [[microcomputer]] and [[Home video game console|console]] platforms by various [[third-party developer]]s, with each one featuring several changes or additions compared to the original release.\n\n''Slap Fight'' proved to be popular for Toaplan among arcades players despite a low number of arcade boards manufactured in Japan, however it was met with mixed reception from video game magazines across western regions, specifically the home [[Video game conversion|conversion]]s. Although it never received a direct sequel, the game's ideas and weapon system were later inherited by both ''[[Truxton (video game)|Truxton]]'' and ''[[Grind Stormer]]'', with the latter being regarded as its [[spiritual successor]]. The rights to the title are owned by Tatsujin, a Japanese company formed by Masahiro Yuge.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:ARC Slap Fight (Alcon).png|thumb|left|Arcade version screenshot.]]\n''Slap Fight'' is a [[science fiction]]-themed vertically scrolling [[shoot 'em up]] game reminiscent of ''[[B-Wings]]'', where players assume the role of an Allied League of Cosmic Nations (ALCON) fighter pilot taking control of the SW475 space fighter craft in a counterattack effort to defeat an invading alien race led by Gaudy on planet Theron as the main objective.<ref name=\"SFMDmanual\">''Slap Fight MD'' manual (Sega Mega Drive, JP)</ref><ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\">{{cite web|last=Kalata|first=Kurt|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/slap-fight-alcon/|title=Slap Fight / ALCON|publisher=Hardcore Gaming 101|date=3 July 2011|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref><ref name=\"SFss\">{{cite web|url=http://shootingstar.game.coocan.jp/slap_fight.html|title=SLAP FIGHT|publisher=Shooting Star|access-date=2020-04-24|language=ja}}</ref> Besides some [[helicopter]]s taking off, there are no flying enemies in the entire game. As far as vertical scrolling shooters go, the title initially appears to be very standard, as players control their craft over a constantly scrolling background and the scenery never stops moving until a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] at the end that must be fought before progressing any further is reached. Players have only two weapons at their disposal: the standard and side shots that travel a max distance of half the screen's height and length.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\"SFss\"/>\n\nThe game's weapon [[power-up]] system takes inspiration from ''[[Gradius]]'';<ref name=\"SFMDmanual\"/><ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\"SFss\"/> certain enemies spawn a [[star]]-shaped [[Item (gaming)|item]] upon destruction to be collected, activating an an upgrade menu at the bottom of the screen that moves a lit cursor through the list of weapon power-ups described below.<ref name=\"SFMDmanual\"/><ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\"SFss\"/> However, activating any weapon power-up increases the ship's [[Collision detection#Hitbox|hitbox]], making it a bigger target for enemy fire and difficult to keep successive lives in the heat of battle.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/> If any power-up is lit but the player's ship is destroyed before a power-up could be selected, the star item is \"carried over\" and the speed power-up is lit on the next life. A number of hidden bonus secrets to be found are hosted, which is also crucial for reaching high-scores to obtain extra lives, as firing on determined locations and certain [[setpiece]]s within the scenery in some stages reveals a bonus secret.\n\nMajor weapons affect the enemies and terrain differently. For example, certain enemy towers can only be destroyed with laser or homing missile shots; other enemies are destroyed much faster with specific weapons to match. If [[bomb]] or homing missile shots are equipped, certain bonus targets will appear or parts of the landscape may be destroyed to reveal bonuses. If laser is active, certain plants in the landscape can be shot repeatedly to grow and earn extra points until they scroll off-screen.<ref name=\"SFss\"/> It has been reported that a bug in the game enabled the player to obtain all power-ups, simply by allowing themselves to be killed by the first enemy appearing upon starting the game without touching the controls. If this occurred, the next time the player's ship appears, it has all the power-ups equipped.<ref>{{cite web|author=smac|url=https://www.rllmukforum.com/index.php?/topic/76529-best-trick-cheat-or-bug-in-an-arcade-game/&do=findComment&comment=1735599|title=Best Trick, Cheat Or Bug In An Arcade Game.. (Page 2)|website=rllmukforum.com|date=16 March 2005|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\nThe game employs a [[Saved game#Checkpoints|checkpoint]] system in which a downed single player will start off at the beginning of the checkpoint they managed to reach before dying.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/> Getting hit by enemy fire will result in losing a live, as well as a penalty of decreasing the ship's [[firepower]] to its original state and once all lives are lost, the [[Game over|game is over]] unless the player inserts more credits into the arcade machine to [[Continue (video games)|continue]] playing. After completing the last stage, the game begins again with the second loop increasing in difficulty and enemies fire denser [[bullet]] patterns. The title does not support continues with extra credits and is believed to loop endlessly.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nThe plot summary of ''Slap Fight'' varies between each region and version.<ref name=\"SFMDmanual\"/><ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\"SFss\"/><ref name=\"ALCONflyer\">''Alcon'' arcade flyer (Taito, US)</ref> The game takes place in the year 2059 on another galaxy, mankind has colonized an alien planet called Theon after evacuating a previously colonized planet Orac. Five years ago, the colony on Orac was attacked by alien invaders and the war was so intense, the colonists were forced to leave. However, Theon is now under attack by the same alien fleet, but the humans are ready. The player assumes the role of an Allied League of Cosmic Nations (ALCON) fighter pilot in the SW475 space fighter craft to stop the invaders from taking over Theon.\n\n== Development ==\n=== Arcade version ===\n[[File:Slap Fight art design.jpg|thumb|right|Most of the artwork were hand-drawn sketches created by the development team before being transpose to [[pixel art]] graphics.]]\n''Slap Fight''{{'}}s development team had a concept for a game that featured secrets, while its main appeal to keep players investing long playtime sessions revolved around hidden items and the weapon power-up system, as then-Toaplan [[Video game composer|composer]] Masahiro Yuge stated that the team's idea for the game was to add many secrets as they could like one of the aliens from ''[[Space Invaders]]'', which was added as an homage to Taito, with Yuge citing his liking of titles with hidden secrets and characters.<ref name=\"PSGv10\">{{cite magazine|last=Abeto|first=Kobatsu|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|magazine=PSG|volume=10|publisher=FSG|date=September 1989|page=|lang=ja}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-psg/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531193430/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-psg/|date=2017-05-31}}).</ref><ref name=\"G49\">{{cite magazine|author=|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3|magazine=[[Gamest]]|issue=49|publisher=[[Shinseisha]]|date=September 1990|page=|lang=ja}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-gamest/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107033548/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-gamest/|date=2019-11-07}}).</ref><ref name=\"TSCb\">{{cite web|url=https://sweeprecord.com/toaplan-shooting-toku/|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3 \u30b7\u30e5\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30af\u30ed\u30cb\u30af\u30eb \u7279\u8a2d\u30da\u30fc\u30b8|work=SweepRecord|publisher=SuperSweep|date=27 October 2011|access-date=2020-04-24|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215231114/https://sweeprecord.com/toaplan-shooting-toku/|archive-date=2020-02-15|url-status=live}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-chronicleqa/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002072400/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-chronicleqa/|date=2019-10-02}}).</ref><ref name=\"STGv4b\">{{cite magazine|last1=Kiyoshi|first1=Tane|author2=hally (VORC)|last3=Y\u016bsaku|first3=Yamamoto|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u7279\u96c6  - \u5143\u30fb\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u3000\u958b\u767a\u8005\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc: \u5f13\u524a\u96c5\u7a14|magazine=Shooting Gameside|volume=4|publisher=Micro Magazine|date=3 February 2012|pages=41-48|lang=ja|ISBN=978-4896373844}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-yuge1/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906023744/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-yuge1/|date=2019-09-06}}).</ref> ''Slap Fight'' was also one of the earliest projects Toaplan made use of [[game design document]]s, though Yuge claimed that these were added after development as postscripts, since the team \"needed some written records\".<ref name=\"TSCa\">{{cite web|url=https://sweeprecord.com/srin-1100/|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3 \u30b7\u30e5\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30af\u30ed\u30cb\u30af\u30eb|work=SweepRecord|publisher=SuperSweep|date=14 November 2011|access-date=2020-04-24|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021030143/https://sweeprecord.com/srin-1100/|archive-date=2019-10-21|url-status=live}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-chronicle/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711134859/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-chronicle/|date=2018-07-11}}).</ref>\n\nYuge stated that the weapon change mechanism was intended to be a strategic element in ''Slap Fight'', as the player's ship is rendered invincible.<ref name=\"TSCb\"/> The weapon power-up system were implemented early during the creation process, since the development wanted to make \"that kind of game\", while each of the weapons' functionality and role were decided to be good for certain sections in the title.<ref name=\"TSCb\"/> All of the secrets were planned from the beginning of development and the team kept adding to the idea during the creation process such as secrets that required certain weapons.<ref name=\"TSCb\"/> Another secret, the ship's satellite \"option\", was an idea suggested by Osamu \"Lee\" \u014cta as a way to give the second player on a [[Arcade cabinet#Cocktail or table cabinets|cocktail cabinet]] a purpose.<ref name=\"TSCb\"/>\n\n=== Mega Drive version ===\n{{Quote box|quote=The ports we did in-house at Toaplan I oversaw completely, but with the ones we licensed out, it was pretty much \"do what you like.\"|source=Former Toaplan composer [[Tatsuya Uemura]] gave ''Slap Fight MD'' its ''{{wiktang|raison d'\u00eatre}}'' when responding about the conversion's [[soundtrack]] by [[Yuzo Koshiro]].<ref name=\"STGv4a\">{{cite magazine|last1=Kiyoshi|first1=Tane|author2=hally (VORC)|last3=Y\u016bsaku|first3=Yamamoto|title=\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u7279\u96c6  - \u5143\u30fb\u6771\u4e9c\u30d7\u30e9\u30f3\u3000\u958b\u767a\u8005\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc: \u4e0a\u6751\u5efa\u4e5f|magazine=Shooting Gameside|volume=4|publisher=Micro Magazine|date=3 February 2012|pages=33-40|lang=ja|ISBN=978-4896373844}} ([http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-uemura1/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906023755/http://shmuplations.com/toaplan-uemura1/|date=2019-09-06}}).</ref>|width=23em|quoted=1}}\nThe [[Sega Mega Drive]] conversion titled ''Slap Fight MD'' was developed by M.N.M Software, a Japanese game development company founded by former Dempa Micomsoft member Mikito Ichikawa.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\">{{cite web|last=Massey|first=Tom|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-12-death-from-above-the-making-of-slap-fight-md|title=Death from Above: The making of Slap Fight MD - Mikito Ichikawa takes us behind the doors of a forgotten classic|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=[[Gamer Network]]|date=5 May 2015|access-date=2019-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320144329/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-12-death-from-above-the-making-of-slap-fight-md|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ichikawa met then-Toaplan composer [[Tatsuya Uemura]] at the home of late ''[[Bubble Bobble]]'' [[Video game designer|designer]] [[Fukio Mitsuji]], exchanging business cards before Ichikawa found the offices of Toaplan two weeks later.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Being a fan of ''[[Twin Cobra]]'', Ichikawa wanted to make a console port but Uemura told him the game was already being converted by another company though the former said if the latter could port ''Slap Fight'' instead, which surprised Ichikawa as the arcade original displayed Taito's logo but accepted the offer since he was a fan of the arcade version.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/>\n\n''Slap Fight MD'', which was a created as a subcontract from Toaplan, was developed concurrently over the course of one year alongside four other projects at M.N.M Software including ''[[Streets of Rage 2]]'', which inflicting both development of the port and Ichikawa's health greatly due to working overtime to the point of working at home on his [[Personal computer|PC]] while his health condition worsened, prompting him with including version information in the project during development as a result.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Uemura served as [[Video game producer|producer]], while [[Video game programmer|programmer]] Jun Shimizu did the coding process entirely by himself and also served as [[level designer]].<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> ''[[Streets of Rage]]'' composer [[Yuzo Koshiro]] was recruited by Ichikawa to score the music due to his experience with M.N.M, while voicework was done by a friend of Koshiro serving at a US military base.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Ichikawa arranged the original arcade music and claimed that M.N.M originally did not have plans to arrange arcade music, however Uemura requested it and after positive feedback from him, led Ichikawa in commit to the task.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Toaplan also provided references materials used during development of the arcade original to the team at M.N.M.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> The cover art was drawn by Parsley Promotion.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/>\n\nThe special mode in ''Slap Fight MD'' was developed by M.N.M due to preoccupation that their conversion would have not featured many content if they followed Toaplan's basic contract of just porting ''Slap Fight'' to the Mega Drive.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Ichikawa stated that the special mode was conceived as the \"ultimate version\" and featured a wider range of strategic play, as the team felt the original arcade release did not offered many gameplay variables.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> Both Toaplan and M.N.M wanted the port to be catered towards casual and hardcore players.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/>\n\n== Release ==\n[[File:MD Slap Fight MD.png|thumb|right|Sega Mega Drive version screenshot, showcasing the game's special mode.]]\n''Slap Fight'' was first released in arcades across Japan on July 1986 and later in North America on September of the same year, as well as in Europe by Taito.<ref name=\"ATVGL:JaO1971-2005\"/>{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Known commercial ports of the game released across European and North American markets include: [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Thomson MO5]], [[Thomson TO8]] and [[ZX Spectrum]]. Almost all microcomputer versions of the game would later be re-released as budget titles by [[Ocean Software|The Hit Squad]] respectively.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nA Sega Mega Drive conversion titled ''Slap Fight MD'' was published in Japan by [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] on 11 June 1993 and South Korea by [[Samsung]] on the same year.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/>{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Tengen produced an estimated run of 5000 copies for the Mega Drive port.<ref name=\"EuroGSFMD\"/> ''Slap Fight MD'' itself is a new special game mode featuring new levels, graphics, weapons and music, plus a new \"bomb\" feature at the cost of wing power-ups and new music composed and arranged by [[Yuzo Koshiro]], which is presented on the title screen.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/> The original game was also included, but with changes such as configuration for the shield's timer and a in-game announcer.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/> \n\nIn ''[[Let's! TV Play Classic#Taito Nostalgia 2|Taito Nostalgia 2]]'' for the ''[[Let's! TV Play Classic]]'' [[Handheld TV game|plug and play game]] series by [[Bandai]], the original Japanese version and a new version titled ''Slap Fight Tiger'' were included.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last=|first=|url=http://www.changevworld.com/letsplay/letsplay.htm|title=Let's! TV play classic|website=www.changevworld.com|publisher=Change-V's Anime and Game collection|access-date=2017-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424215620/http://www.changevworld.com/letsplay/letsplay.htm|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In this version, players control the titular attack helicopter from ''[[Tiger-Heli]]'' instead of the SW475, while the laser is changed to fire a three-way spread shot and new enemies such as the aliens from ''Space Invaders'' are introduced.<ref name=\"SFALCONhg101\"/><ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Reception ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:80%; text-align:center; margin:1em; margin-top:0; padding:0; background:none;\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! colspan=10 style=\"font-size: 100%\" | Reception\n|-\n! colspan=7 | Review scores\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Publication\n! colspan=7 | Scores\n|-\n! [[Amstrad CPC|CPC]]\n! [[Commodore 64|C64]]\n! [[Thomson computers|Thomson]]\n! [[ZX Spectrum|